  "prompt": "Why isn't hockey the national game of India?",
  "response": "Hockey is often considered India's national game due to its historical success and prominence, especially during the mid-20th century when India dominated international hockey, winning multiple Olympic gold medals (eight in total, with six consecutive wins from 1928 to 1956). However, **it is not officially recognized as the national game of India**.\n\nDespite its rich legacy, there is no official declaration by the Government of India designating hockey (or any other sport) as the national game. This is often a point of confusion because many people assume hockey holds this status due to its historical importance.\n\nIn 2012, the Indian government clarified in response to a Right to Information (RTI) query that **no sport has been officially declared as the national game of India**. While hockey remains a symbol of India's sporting heritage, other sports like cricket have gained immense popularity and cultural significance in the country over the years. \n\nThe absence of an official national game reflects India's diverse sporting culture, where multiple sports hold significance for different regions and communities.",
